so, the compiled function is essentially reading a book entry (statically, at
compile time) and performing static-time interactions against a dynamic stack.
it performs static ALO interactions to read the current term to be compiled,
then, if it is a LAM, it emits a pop from the dynamic stack, and then it checks
if it is a supported interaction pattern - in this case, an APP. if so, then, in
that branch, it does a "static app-lam", putting the result in a register, and
moving on. the catch is that the compiler is basically emulating how the runtime
would unroll ALO's, plus a subset of all interactions matching the allocated
term against the dynamic stack. when it finds an unsupported interaction, it
falls back to an ALO node. because of that, we *must* emulate the ALO subst map
statically. that's mandatory. this also tells us how to handle DUP nodes
correctly. notice that, when we compile a DUP, we do *NOT* create a DUP node
immediatelly. instead, we extend the "static subst map" (which is a compile time
value) with an ALO of the expression. this allows us to reconstruct the correct
subst list later, if we get stuck, AND it allows us to perform static
interactions involving DUP, like we did on the example above. notice that, on
that example, we computed x=3+3 without falling back to alo nodes, in the
compiled hot paths!  so, the goal of the compiler is to produce a C function
that pattern-matches on the static, doing all interactions of each possible
branch statically, avoiding ALO nodes for as long as possible, but properly
falling back to them when needed. that's it!

